Reisen eines Deutschen in England i m Jahre 1782 ( English : Journeys of a German in England in 1782 ) is a travel memoir by German author Karl Philipp Moritz .
Hegemony and Socialist Strategy is a 1985 work of political theory in the post - Marxist tradition by Ernesto Laclau and Chantal Mouffe .
Smart Women is a 1983 novel by Judy Blume that tells the story of a divorcee who falls for her friend 's ex - husband .
Ardèle ou la Marguerite is a 1948 play by French dramatist Jean Anouilh .
The Zombies That Ate The World ( French : Les Zombies qui ont mangé le monde ) is an ongoing comic book series written by Jerry Frissen and illustrated by Guy Davis .
Keepers of the House is the debut novel of Lisa St Aubin de Terán , published as The Long Way Home in the US .
The Romany Rye is a novel by George Borrow , written in 1857 .
Banquets of the Black Widowers is a collection of mystery short stories by science fiction author Isaac Asimov featuring his fictional club of mystery solvers , the Black Widowers .
Doors Open is a 2008 novel by crime writer Ian Rankin .
Armageddon in Retrospect is a collection of short stories and essays about war and peace written by Kurt Vonnegut .
The Epicurean is a novel by Thomas Moore , published in 1827 .
Odes et Ballades , published in 1828 , is the most complete version of a collection of poems by Victor Hugo written and published between 1822 and 1828 .
`` The Adventure of the Unique Dickensians '' is a detective fiction short story by author August Derleth .
A Little Lumpen Novelita ( Una novelita lumpen in Spanish ) is a novel by the Chilean author Roberto Bolaño .
The Destruction of the European Jews is a book published in 1961 by historian Raul Hilberg .
The Corridors of Time is a science fiction novel by Poul Anderson , first published in 1966 as serial in Amazing Stories , May - June 1965 and as book by Doubleday .
`` To Build a Fire '' is the title of two short stories by American author Jack London , published in 1902 and 1908 .
Something Like a House is the debut novel by British writer Sid Smith , first published in 2001 .
The Canterbury Tales ( Middle English : Tales of Caunterbury ) is a collection of 24 stories that runs to over 17,000 lines written in Middle English by Geoffrey Chaucer .
Erewhon : or , Over the Range ( e - re - whon ) is a novel by Samuel Butler which was first published anonymously in 1872 .
Dragonflight is a science fiction novel by the American - Irish author Anne McCaffrey .
The Castle of Wolfenbach ( 1793 ) is the most famous novel written by the English Gothic novelist Eliza Parsons .
The Devil 's Teardrop is a novel published in 1999 , written by author Jeffery Deaver .
Outside the Dog Museum is a novel by the American writer Jonathan Carroll , published in 2005 .
Capital in the Twenty - First Century is a 2013 book by French economist Thomas Piketty .
At Swim , Two Boys ( 2001 ) is a novel by Irish writer Jamie O'Neill .
Wintermind is the second novel of the Masters of Solitude trilogy , written by authors Marvin Kaye and Parke Godwin .
Sixth Grade Secrets is a novel by Louis Sachar that follows sixth - grader Laura Sibbie and her friends as they create a secret club in violation of school rules .
The Sibling Society is a book by poet , activist and author Robert Bly , published in 1996 .
A Solitary Grief ( 1991 ) is a novel by Bernice Rubens about a Harley Street doctor who can not cope with his own life .
Something Rotten is the fourth book in the Thursday Next series by Jasper Fforde .
The 50th Law is a New York Times bestselling book on strategy and fearlessness written collaboratively by rapper 50 Cent and author Robert Greene .
On the Black Hill is a novel by Bruce Chatwin published in 1982 and winner of the James Tait Black Memorial Prize for that year .
Meet the Austins is the title of a 1960 novel by Madeleine L'Engle , the first of her books about the Austin family .
Four Quartets is a set of four poems written by T. S. Eliot that were published individually over a six - year period .
The Cinder Path is a novel by Catherine Cookson and a 1994 film directed by Simon Langton and based on the novel .
A Tree of Night and Other Stories is a short story collection by the American author Truman Capote published in early 1949 .
Call Me Bandicoot is a 1970 young adult novel written by U.S. author William Pène du Bois .
The 1972 Annual World 's Best SF is an anthology of science fiction short stories edited by Donald A. Wollheim and Arthur W. Saha , the initial volume in a series of nineteen .
Bibliotheca historica ( Βιβλιοθήκη ἱστορική , `` Historical Library '' ) , is a work of universal history by Diodorus Siculus .
Angels and Spaceships is a 1954 collection of science fiction and fantasy stories by Fredric Brown .
The Charioteer of Delphi is a children 's historical novel by Caroline Lawrence , published in 2006 .
Executive Order 11110 was issued by U.S. President John F. Kennedy on June 4 , 1963 .
Oru Sankeerthanam Pole ( Malayalam : ഒരു സങ്കീർത്തനം പോലെ ) is a widely acclaimed novel written by Perumbadavam Sreedharan , first published in September , 1993 .
The Doll People is a children 's novel written by Ann M. Martin and Laura Godwin , first published in 2000 .
`` Young Zaphod Plays It Safe '' is a short story by Douglas Adams set in his The Hitchhiker 's Guide to the Galaxy universe .
Erections , Ejaculations , Exhibitions , and General Tales of Ordinary Madness was a paperback collection of short stories by Charles Bukowski , first published by City Lights Publishers in 1972 .
Dead Accounts is Broadway play written by Theresa Rebeck .
The Holy Sinner ( in German , Der Erwählte ) is a German novel written by Thomas Mann .
The Bridal Canopy ( Hebrew : הכנסת כלה‎ , Hakhnasat Kallah ) , a novel by Shmuel Yosef Agnon , is considered to be one of the first classics of modern Hebrew literature .
The Mars trilogy is a series of award - winning science fiction novels by Kim Stanley Robinson that chronicles the settlement and terraforming of the planet Mars through the intensely personal and detailed viewpoints of a wide variety of characters spanning almost two centuries .
The Aspern Papers is a novella written by Henry James , originally published in The Atlantic Monthly in 1888 , with its first book publication later in the same year .
`` The Argonauts of the Air '' is a short story by H. G. Wells , first published in 1895 in Phil May 's Annual .
The High Crusade is a science fiction novel by Poul Anderson about the consequences of an extraterrestrial scoutship landing in Medieval England .
The Greater Inclination was the earliest collection of short fiction by Edith Wharton .
Schweik in the Second World War ( Schweyk i m Zweiten Weltkrieg ) is a play by German dramatist and poet Bertolt Brecht .
Black Summer is a comic book limited series written by Warren Ellis , illustrated by Juan Jose Ryp , and published by Avatar Press starting in June 2007 .
Thirteen Steps Down ( 2004 ) is a psychological thriller novel by Ruth Rendell .
The Lowland is the second novel by Jhumpa Lahiri , published by Alfred A. Knopf and Random House in 2013 .
Ramona the Pest , by Beverly Cleary , is the second book of the Ramona series and the first to focus on Ramona Quimby as the protagonist .
Gladiator - At - Law is a satirical science fiction novel by Frederik Pohl and Cyril M. Kornbluth .
The Light 's on at Signpost is a memoir from George MacDonald Fraser covering his various adventures in screenwriting as well as essays on the state of modern - day England .
The Magic Bicycle is the first novel of the Spirit Flyer Series by John Bibee and illustrated by Paul Turnbaugh .
Orchids , a collection of prose and poetry ( Dutch : Orchideeën , een bundel proza en poëzie ) is a collection of prose and poetry written by Dutch writer Louis Couperus , which was published in 1886 .
The Dehumanization of Art and Other Essays on Art , Culture , and Literature is the first English translation of philosopher José Ortega y Gasset 's `` La deshumanización del Arte e Ideas sobre la novela '' , published in 1925 .
Nélida is a novel by Marie d'Agoult , a `` thinly disguised fictional account '' of her four - year affair with composer Franz Liszt , and a succès de scandale when first published in 1846 .
Kings Will Be Tyrants by Ward Hawkins is a 1959 novel about fighting in Cuba .
Marks of Identity ( Spanish : Señas de identidad ) is a 1966 novel by the Spanish writer Juan Goytisolo .
Sachs and Violens is a fictional comic book duo created by American writer Peter David and co - developed with George Pérez .
The Fate of a Crown is a 1905 adventure novel written by L. Frank Baum , the author best known for his Oz books .
In Siberia is a 1999 travel book by the English writer Colin Thubron .
Comic - book stories of the character scripted by John Stanley appeared in ten issues of Dell 's Four Color before a Marge 's Little Lulu series appeared in 1948 .
The Exception and the Rule ( in German Die Ausnahme und die Regel ) is a short play by German playwright Bertolt Brecht and is one of several Lehrstücke ( Teaching plays ) he wrote around 1929/30 .
Plague Ship is a science fiction novel by author Andrew North ( pseudonym of Alice Mary Norton , also known as Andre Norton ) .
The One Day of the Year is an Australian play by Alan Seymour originally written in 1958 about Anzac Day .
The Wizard of Venus is a novella by Edgar Rice Burroughs , as well as the title of a collection in which it was later published together with an unrelated story .
Genius Squad is a novel written by Catherine Jinks published in 2008 by Allen & Unwin , Australia .
`` The Lottery in Babylon '' ( or `` The Babylon Lottery '' ; original Spanish `` La lotería en Babilonia '' ) is a fantasy short story by Argentinian writer Jorge Luis Borges .
L'Ingénu is a satirical novella by the French writer Voltaire , published in 1767 .
What They Always Tell Us is the first novel by Martin Wilson , focusing on the relationship between two high school age brothers as one begins to embrace his homosexuality .
A Perfect Spy ( 1986 ) by British author John le Carré is a novel about the mental and moral dissolution of a high level secret agent .
Letters from the Earth is a posthumously published work of celebrated American author Mark Twain ( 1835 - -1910 ) .
Babylon Babies is the third novel by French - born naturalized Canadian writer Maurice G. Dantec , published in 1999 .
With the People from the Bridge ( Greek : Με τους ανθρώπους από τη γέφυρα ) is the second part of the Poena Damni trilogy by Greek author Dimitris Lyacos .
The Pinballs is a 1976 young adult novel by American author Betsy Byars .
The Squirrel Wife is the title of a children 's fairy tale written by Philippa Pearce and first illustrated by Derek Collard .
The Return of Chorb is a short story by Vladimir Nabokov written in Russian under his pen name Vladimir Sirin in Berlin in 1925 .
No New Land is a novel by M. G. Vassanji , published in 1991 .
Rainbow Boys is the first novel in a trilogy by Alex Sánchez , focusing on the issues gay and questioning youth face as they come of age .
`` My Son , the Physicist '' is a science fiction short story by American writer Isaac Asimov .
Dragonsinger is a young adult science fiction novel by the American - Irish author Anne McCaffrey .
The History of a Town is a fictional chronicle by Mikhail Saltykov - Shchedrin first published in 1870 and regarded as the major satirical Russian novel of the 19th century .
The Luck of Barry Lyndon is a picaresque novel by William Makepeace Thackeray , first published in serial form in 1844 , about a member of the Irish gentry trying to become a member of the English aristocracy .
Interesting Times is the seventeenth novel in the Discworld series by Terry Pratchett , set in the Aurient ( aka Orient ) .
In the Country of Men is the debut novel of Libyan writer Hisham Matar , first published in 2006 by Viking , an imprint of Penguin Books .
`` The Very Pulse of the Machine '' is a science fiction short story published in 1998 by Michael Swanwick .
Gib Rides Home is a 1998 novel for young readers by Zilpha Keatley Snyder .
Dyr bul shchyl ( Russian : Дыр бул щыл , ( dɨr bul ɕːɨl ) ) is the earliest and most famous transrational poem by Aleksei Kruchenykh , written using the Zaum language , which , according to the author , is `` more Russian national , than in all of Pushkin 's poetry '' .
Week - end at Zuydcoote ( French : Week - end à Zuydcoote ) is a 1949 novel by French author Robert Merle .
Sign of Chaos is the Locus Award nominated third novel in the second Chronicles of Amber series by Roger Zelazny , and the eighth book overall .
The Southern Victory series or Timeline-191 are fan names given to a series of eleven alternate history novels by author Harry Turtledove , beginning with How Few Remain ( 1997 ) and published over a decade .
Wogs Out of Work is an Australian play which was written by Nick Giannopoulos , Simon Palomares , and Maria Portesi .
`` The King of the Elves '' is a short story by science fiction writer Philip K. Dick and first published in the September 1953 issue of Beyond Fantasy Fiction .
Two Minor Ethical - Religious Essays ( original Danish title : Tvende ethisk - religieuse Smaa - Afhandlinger ) is a work by the Danish philosopher Søren Kierkegaard , under the pseudonym H.H. , written in 1847 and published on May 19 , 1849 .
The Borrowers Afield is a children 's fantasy novel by Mary Norton , published in 1955 by Dent in the UK and Harcourt in the US .
The Two of Them is a feminist science fiction novel by Joanna Russ .
Daisy - Head Mayzie is a children 's book written by Dr. Seuss and illustrated in his style .
The Dialogue in Hell Between Machiavelli and Montesquieu ( in the original French Dialogue aux enfers entre Machiavel et Montesquieu ou la politique de Machiavel au XIXe siècle ) is a political satire written by French attorney Maurice Joly in protest against the regime of Napoleon III , a.k.a . Louis - Napoléon Bonaparte .
Adelchi ( Italian pronunciation : ( aˈdɛlki ) ) is the second tragedy written by Alessandro Manzoni .
`` The Cats of Ulthar '' is a short story written by American fantasy author H. P. Lovecraft in June 1920 .
The Power of Sympathy : or , The Triumph of Nature ( 1789 ) is an 18th - century American sentimental novel written in epistolary form by William Hill Brown , widely considered to be the first American novel .
The Pine Deep Trilogy is a series of supernatural horror novels by Jonathan Maberry .
The Sunset Limited is a play by American writer Cormac McCarthy .
Mararía ( 1973 ) is the most famous novel by the Spanish Canarian writer Rafael Arozarena .
The Positronic Man is a 1992 novel by Isaac Asimov and Robert Silverberg , based on Asimov 's novella The Bicentennial Man .
The Bad Place is a novel written by the best - selling author Dean Koontz , released in 1990 .
The Exhaustive Concordance of the Bible , generally known as Strong 's Concordance , is a concordance of the King James Version ( KJV ) that was constructed under the direction of Dr. James Strong ( 1822 - -1894 ) and first published in 1890 .
Going to the Dogs is a 1986 play by Dutch writer , artist , and television director Wim T. Schippers .
Roadmarks is a science fantasy novel written by Roger Zelazny during the late 1970s and published in 1979 .
Aspects of Anglo - Saxon Magic is a study of Anglo - Saxon paganism and the role of magic in Anglo - Saxon England that was written by the English poet and independent scholar Bill Griffiths .
`` On the Pulse of Morning '' is a poem by African - American writer and poet Maya Angelou that she read at the first inauguration of President Bill Clinton on January 20 , 1993 .
Lost in the Garden is a midlife - crisis novel by the American writer Philip Beard .
Deconstructing Sammy is a critically acclaimed book by author Matt Birkbeck about the life and death of Sammy Davis , Jr. and the subsequent efforts to restore his legacy .
`` The Tree on the Hill '' is a short story written by horror author H. P. Lovecraft and Duane W. Rimel .
Kids on Strike ! is a 2003 non - fiction book written by award winning author Susan Campbell Bartoletti .
DL5 Dragons of Mystery was written by Michael Dobson , with art by Larry Elmore , and was published by TSR in 1984 as a 32-page booklet with an outer folder .
Nobody 's Buddy is an American children 's novel written by John A. Moroso and published in 1936 by Goldsmith Publishing Co. of Chicago , Illinois .
A Battle of Nerves ( French : La Tête d'un homme , also known as A Man 's Head ) is a detective novel by Belgian writer Georges Simenon .
The Essential Tagore is the largest collection of Rabindranath Tagore 's works available in English .
Introduction to Automata Theory , Languages , and Computation is an influential computer science textbook by John Hopcroft and Jeffrey Ullman on formal languages and the theory of computation .
That Awful Mess on Via Merulana is an Italian novel by Carlo Emilio Gadda , first published in Italy by Garzanti Editore s.p.a .
The Descendants of Cain ( 카인의 후예 ) is a novel by Hwang Sun - won ( 황순원 ) .
Good - Bye to All That , an autobiography by Robert Graves , first appeared in 1929 , when the author was thirty - four .
The Wizard of the Emerald City ( Russian : Волшебник Изумрудного Города ) is a 1939 children 's novel by Russian writer Alexander Melentyevich Volkov .
O Pioneers ! is a 1913 novel by American author Willa Cather , written while she was living in New York .
John Dough and the Cherub is a children 's fantasy novel written by L. Frank Baum , about a living gingerbread man and his adventures .
The Phoenix and the Mirror was published in 1969 and is the first novel in the first Vergil Magus series , written by Avram Davidson .
A Writer 's Life is a 2006 autobiography by Gay Talese .
Two Hundred Years Together ( Rus . Двести лет вместе , Dvesti let vmeste ) is a two - volume historical essay by Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn .
Autumn Maze is a 1994 novel from Australian author Jon Cleary .
The Train Was on Time ( German : Der Zug war pünktlich ) is the first published novel by German author Heinrich Böll .
Come , Tell Me How You Live is a short book of autobiography and travel literature by crime writer Agatha Christie .
Wrath of the Lion is a 1964 thriller novel by Jack Higgins .
Ethical Relativity is a 1932 book by the Finnish philosopher Edvard Westermarck , one of his main works .
`` Exploration Team '' is a science fiction novelette by American writer Murray Leinster , originally published in the March 1956 issue of Astounding Science Fiction .
The Second Book of General Ignorance is the fifth in a series of books based on the final round in the intellectual British panel game QI , written by series - creator John Lloyd and head - researcher John Mitchinson .
The Life and Adventures of Martin Chuzzlewit ( commonly known as Martin Chuzzlewit ) is a novel by Charles Dickens , considered the last of his picaresque novels .
One King 's Way is the second part of the trilogy by Harry Harrison and John Holm that began with The Hammer and the Cross .
Berts vidare betraktelser ( Swedish : Bert 's further contemplations ) is a diary novel , written by Anders Jacobsson and Sören Olsson and originally published in 1990 .
After America is an alternate history novel written by British - born Australian author John Birmingham and released in Australia in July 2010 .
Trial of Champions is a single - player roleplaying gamebook , written by Ian Livingstone , illustrated by Brian Williams and originally published in 1986 by Puffin Books .
The Fallon Blood is a novel written by fantasy author James Oliver Rigney , Jr. ( more commonly known as Robert Jordan ) under the name Reagan O'Neal .
Private Angelo was written by Scottish author Eric Linklater and first published in 1946 .
After the Flood ( Swedish : Efter floden ) is a 1982 novel by the Swedish novelist P. C. Jersild .
`` I Wandered Lonely as a Cloud '' ( also commonly known as `` Daffodils '' ) is a lyric poem by William Wordsworth .
The Tales of Alvin Maker is a series of alternate history novels by Orson Scott Card , published from 1987 to 2003 ( with one more planned ) , that explore the experiences of a young man , Alvin Miller , who realizes he has incredible powers for creating and shaping things around him .
Hecate and Her Dogs ( French : Hécate et ses chiens ) is a novel by the French writer Paul Morand .
The Blue Hussar ( French : Le hussard bleu ) is a 1950 novel by the French writer Roger Nimier .
Hijo de hombre ( Son of Man , 1960 ) is a novel by the Paraguayan author Augusto Roa Bastos Roa Bastos ' first published novel , Hijo de hombre represents his definitive break with poetry .
Waiting for the Rain ( 1987 ) by Sheila Gordon tells the story of two boys , one black and one white , growing up on a farm in South Africa during Apartheid .
The Final Descent is a horror novel by Rick Yancey , the fourth and final book in a series that he inaugurated in 2009 with The Monstrumologist ( UK title , The Terror Beneath ) .
The Mediterranean Caper ( also published as Mayday ) is an action - adventure novel by Clive Cussler published in the United States in 1973 .
The Oksa Pollock is a series of six fantasy children 's novels by Anne Plichota and Cendrine Wolf .
They Came on Viking Ships is a children 's historical novel by Jackie French , first published in Australia in 2005 .
The Maker of Universes ( 1965 ) is a fantasy novel by American science fiction author Philip José Farmer .
Eros e Priapo : da furore a cenere is a 1945 satiric pamphlet by Italian author Carlo Emilio Gadda .
The Wandering Scholars is a non - fiction book by Helen Waddell , first published in 1927 by Constable , London .
The Mageborn Traitor , is a fantasy novel written by author Melanie Rawn .
Mr and Mrs Dove is a 1921 short story by Katherine Mansfield .
The Natural History and Antiquities of Selborne , or just The Natural History of Selborne is a book by English naturalist and ornithologist Gilbert White .
Flowers from the Moon and Other Lunacies is a collection of horror and fantasy stories by author Robert Bloch .
Poenulus , also called The Little Carthaginian or The Little Punic , is a Latin comedic play for the early Roman theatre by Titus Maccius Plautus , probably written between 195 and 189 BC . The play is noteworthy for containing text in Carthaginian Punic , spoken by the character Hanno in the fifth act .
Northward Ho ( or Ho ! , or Hoe ) is an early Jacobean era stage play , a satire and city comedy written by Thomas Dekker and John Webster , and first published in 1607 .
Logic as a Positive Science is one of the major works of Italian Marxist philosopher Galvano Della Volpe .
The Mixed Men is a collection of short stories by author A. E. van Vogt that focus on the mixed offspring of Dellian Supermen and human beings .
Girl with Curious Hair is a collection of short stories by David Foster Wallace first published in 1989 .
Chickenfeed ( 2006 ) is a crime novella by English writer Minette Walters , published as part of the `` Quick Reads '' , designed to promote literacy through short , simply written and fast moving stories .
Adventures of Wim or ( reissued in 2002 as Whim ) is a book by George Cockcroft , written under the pen name Luke Rhinehart .
The Bugalugs Bum Thief ( 1991 ) is a children 's novel by acclaimed Australian author Tim Winton .
Lives of the Most Eminent English Poets ( 1779 - -81 ) is a work by Samuel Johnson , comprising short biographies and critical appraisals of 52 poets , most of whom lived during the eighteenth century .
Romiette and Julio by is a novel Sharon Draper , published in 2001 by Simon Pulse .
A Hacker Manifesto is a critical manifesto written by McKenzie Wark , which criticizes the commodification of information in the age of digital culture and globalization .
Whose War Is It ? is a non - fiction book by Jack Granatstein ( published J.L. Granatstein ) , a Canadian historian and military veteran .
Marianne and Mark ( 1960 ) by Catherine Storr is a sequel to Marianne Dreams ( 1958 ) .
Doña Rosita the Spinster ( Spanish : Doña Rosita la soltera ) is a period play by the 20th - century Spanish dramatist Federico García Lorca .
Nice Work ( 1988 ) is a novel by British author David Lodge .
Where Late the Sweet Birds Sang is a science fiction novel written by Kate Wilhelm , published in 1976 .
The Cat Who Could Read Backwards is the first novel in Lilian Jackson Braun 's `` The Cat Who ... '' series , published in 1966 .
Incident at Hawk 's Hill is a Newbery Honor book by naturalist and writer Allan W. Eckert published in 1971 .
Farmer Boy is a children 's historical novel written by Laura Ingalls Wilder and published in 1933 .
Robur the Conqueror ( French : Robur - le - Conquérant ) is a science fiction novel by Jules Verne , published in 1886 .
The Black Riders and Other Lines is a book of poetry written by American author Stephen Crane ( 1871 - -1900 ) .
When Santa Fell to Earth ( German : Als der Weihnachtsmann von Himmel fiel ) is a 2004 novel by German author Cornelia Funke .
Dou E Yuan , commonly translated as The Injustice to Dou E , and also known as The Injustice Done to Tou Ngo and Snow in Midsummer , is a Chinese play written by Guan Hanqing ( c. 1241 - -1320 ) during the Yuan dynasty .
Bitter Lemons is an autobiographical work by writer Lawrence Durrell , describing the three years ( 1953 - -1956 ) he spent on the island of Cyprus .
Guillaume de Dole ( also known as ( Le ) Roman(s ) de la Rose , or Guillaume de Dole ) is an Old French narrative romance by Jean Renart .
Gli Asolani ( the people of Asolo ) are dialogues in 3 books written between 1497 and 1504 by Pietro Bembo in the language of Petrarch and comprise his first important work .
Stones in His Pockets is a two - hander written in 1996 by Marie Jones for the DubbleJoint Theatre Company in Dublin , Ireland .
Mara , Daughter of the Nile by Eloise Jarvis McGraw is a historical fiction children 's book .
' Tis is a memoir written by Frank McCourt .
Prolegomena to Any Future Metaphysics That Will Be Able to Present Itself as a Science ( German : Prolegomena zu einer jeden künftigen Metaphysik , die als Wissenschaft wird auftreten können ) is a book by the German philosopher Immanuel Kant , published in 1783 , two years after the first edition of his Critique of Pure Reason .
Lord Darcy Investigates is a collection of short stories by Randall Garrett featuring his alternate history detective Lord Darcy .
Happy Lesson is a comedy manga , written by Mutsumi Sasaki and illustrated by Shinnosuke Mori , serialized in Dengeki G 's Magazine from April 1999 to September 2002 , featuring a high school student who is adopted by five of his teachers .
A History of Marriage , published by Seven Stories Press , is a non - fiction book by Elizabeth Abbott , the Canadian author of A History of Celibacy ( 1999 ) and A History of Mistresses ( 2003 ) that combines general history and personal histories of marriage .

Two - Minute Drill is a 2007 children 's book by Mike Lupica and the first book in his Comeback Kids series .
A Arma Escarlate ( English : The Scarlet Weapon ) is a 2011 romance novel by Brazilian writer Renata Ventura and released by Novo Século publisher .
Thanks to My Mother is the memoir of Schoschana Rabinovici , née Susanne Weksler , a young Jewish girl from Vilnius , Lithuania .
Leaving the Atocha Station ( 2011 ) is the debut novel by American poet and critic Ben Lerner .
Dust of the Damned is a 2012 novel by Western author Peter Brandvold .
Kushiel 's Scion is the 2006 novel by Jacqueline Carey , following on from the Kushiel 's Legacy trilogy ( Kushiel 's Dart , Kushiel 's Chosen , and Kushiel 's Avatar ) .
`` Sunjammer '' is a science fiction short story by Arthur C. Clarke , originally published in 1963 , and included in the March 1964 issue of Boys ' Life .
Pobby and Dingan is a novella by English author Ben Rice , which first appeared in issue 70 of Granta in Summer 2000 and published in book form later that year .
The Same River ( Estonian : Seesama jõgi ) is a semi - autobiographical novel by Estonian author Jaan Kaplinski .
Tasuke , the Samurai Cop , known in Japanese as Edokko Boy Gatten Tasuke ( 江戸っ子ボーイがってん太助 Edokko Bōi Gatten Tasuke ) , is a manga series created by Manavu Kashimoto .
What I Call Life is a young adult novel by Jill Wolfson .
Bag Limit is a crime novel written by Steven F. Havill .
The Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices ( MUTCD ) is a document issued by the Federal Highway Administration ( FHWA ) of the United States Department of Transportation ( USDOT ) to specify the standards by which traffic signs , road surface markings , and signals are designed , installed , and used .
The Ingenuity Gap is a non - fiction book by Canadian academic Thomas Homer - Dixon .
Alan Mendelsohn , the Boy from Mars is a novel by Daniel Pinkwater , published in 1979 .
The Vanished Diamond , also translated as The Southern Star ( French : L'Étoile du sud , lit . The Star of the South ) is a novel by Jules Verne , first published in 1884 .
Ginger You 're Barmy ( 1962 ) is a comic novel by David Lodge based on his experiences as a conscript to two years National Service in post - war Britain between August 1955 and August 1957 .
`` Mr F. is Mr F. '' is a short story by British author J. G. Ballard .
Asterix and Son is the twenty - seventh volume of the Asterix comic book series , created by author René Goscinny and illustrator Albert Uderzo .
Os Sertões ( translated as Rebellion in the Backlands ) ( 1902 ) is a book written by the Brazilian author Euclides da Cunha .
How to Solve It ( 1945 ) is a small volume by mathematician George Pólya describing methods of problem solving .
The English Roses is a 2003 children 's picture book written by American entertainer Madonna and illustrated by Jeffrey Fulvimari , which later became a series of children 's books by both artists .
A Grief Observed is a collection of C. S. Lewis 's reflections on the experience of bereavement following the death of his wife , Joy Davidman , in 1960 .
Executive Order 10988 is a United States presidential executive order issued by President John F. Kennedy on January 17 , 1962 that recognized the right of federal employees to collective bargaining .
Dies the Fire is a 2004 alternate history and post - apocalyptic novel written by S. M. Stirling .
From a Crooked Rib is the first published novel by Somalian novelist Nuruddin Farah .
An Age ( published in the U.S. as Cryptozoic ! ) is a 1967 science fiction novel by Brian Aldiss .
Heroes of the Fiery Cross is a book in praise of the Ku Klux Klan , published in 1928 by Protestant Bishop Alma Bridwell White , in which she `` sounds the alarm about imagined threats to Protestant Americans from Catholics and Jews '' , according to author Peter Knight .
Judge Dee at Work is a collection of gong'an detective short stories written by Robert van Gulik and set in Imperial China ( roughly speaking the Tang Dynasty ) .
M*A*S*H Goes to Maine is a novel written by Richard Hooker and originally published in 1972 .
The Small Assassin ( 1962 ) is a short story collection by Ray Bradbury .
Hunter 's Moon , known as The Foxes of Firstdark in the United States , is a novel by English fantasy author Garry Kilworth , published in 1989 .
`` Syzyfowe prace '' or `` Labors of Sisyphus '' is a novel by Polish author Stefan Żeromski which first appeared in the magazine Nowa Reforma in 1897 .
Lord Mord is a Czech historical novel , written by Miloš Urban .
Le Spleen de Paris , also known as Paris Spleen or Petits Poèmes en prose , is a collection of 51 short prose poems by Charles Baudelaire .
Under the Sunset is a collection of short stories by Bram Stoker ( the author of Dracula ) , first published in 1881 .
The Final Programme is a novel by British science fiction and fantasy writer Michael Moorcock .
A Life in the Theatre is a 1977 play by David Mamet .
Dreaming Down - Under is a 1998 speculative fiction anthology edited by Jack Dann and Janeen Webb
True at First Light is a book by American novelist Ernest Hemingway about his 1953 - -54 East African safari with his fourth wife Mary , released posthumously in his centennial year in 1999 .
Created By is a 1993 horror novel by Richard Christian Matheson .
Babel-17 is a 1966 science fiction novel by American writer Samuel R. Delany in which the Sapir--
Half a Team is a 1980 children 's novel by prolific British author Michael Hardcastle .
Twenty Five Years of an Artist is a 1993 photography book chronicling the long career of David Hamilton .
Cage of Stars ( ISBN 9780446578752 ) is a 2006 best - selling novel by Jacquelyn Mitchard .
The Cat Who Sniffed Glue is the eighth book in The Cat Who ... mystery series by Lilian Jackson Braun , published in 1988 .
Not That Sort of Girl ( 1987 ) is a novel by British author Mary Wesley .
The Arte de la lengua mexicana con la declaración de los adverbios della is a grammar of the Nahuatl language in Spanish by Jesuit grammarian Horacio Carochi .
Show of Evil is a 1995 novel by William Diehl , the sequel to Primal Fear .
`` The Judgment '' ( `` Das Urteil '' ) is a short story written by Franz Kafka in 1912 , concerning the relationship between a man and his father .
Planning the Play of a Bridge Hand is a book on contract bridge co - written by Canadian teacher and author Barbara Seagram and British author David Bird .
The Indiscreet Jewels ( or The Indiscreet Toys , or The Talking Jewels , French : Les bijoux indiscrets ) is the first novel by Denis Diderot , published anonymously in 1748 .
A Flea in Her Ear ( in French : La Puce à l'oreille ) is a play by Georges Feydeau written in 1907 , at the height of the Belle Époque .
Pretty , Baby , Machine ( also known as Pretty Baby Machine ) is a three - issue comic book limited series written by Clark Westerman with art by Kody Chamberlain , and released by Image Comics through their ShadowLine studio in 2008 .
The Old Glory is a play written by the American poet Robert Lowell that was first performed in 1964 .
King Hedley II is a play by American playwright August Wilson , the eighth in his ten - part series , The Pittsburgh Cycle .
Saving Faith , written by David Baldacci , is a thriller novel set with backdrop of the political lobbying , political corruption , and blackmail in the US Government .
The Ghost Road is a war novel by Pat Barker , first published in 1995 and winner of the Booker Prize .
Atalanta Fugiens or Atalanta Fleeing is an emblem book by Michael Maier ( 1568 - -1622 ) , published by Johann Theodor de Bry in Oppenheim in 1617 ( 2nd edition 1618 ) .
Nicholas Nickleby ; or , The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby is a novel by Charles Dickens .
The Bureau for Paranormal Research and Defense ( the B.P.R.D. or BPRD ) is a fictional organization in the comic book work of Mike Mignola , charged with protecting America and the world from the occult , paranormal and supernatural .
The Marvelous Palace And Other Stories ( French : ' Histoires Perfides ' ) is a collection of short stories by French author Pierre Boulle , published in French in 1976 and in English in 1977 .
Spilling The Beans is an autobiography written by Clarissa Dickson Wright and first published in 2007 .
The Eagle of the Ninth is a historical adventure novel for children written by Rosemary Sutcliff and published in 1954 .
The Nine Wrong Answers , first published in 1952 , is a detective story by John Dickson Carr which does not feature any of Carr 's series detectives .
Gods of Riverworld ( 1983 ) is a science fiction novel , the fifth and last in the series of Riverworld books by Philip José Farmer .
`` Survivor Type '' is a short story by Stephen King , first published in the 1982 horror anthology Terrors , edited by Charles L. Grant , and collected in King 's 1985 collection Skeleton Crew .
In the Sargasso Sea is a children 's novel written in 1898 by Thomas Allibone Janvier .
A Philosophical Enquiry into the Origin of Our Ideas of the Sublime and Beautiful is a 1757 treatise on aesthetics written by Edmund Burke .
Flight of the Fire Thief is a novel written by Terry Deary , and is the second installment of The Fire Thief Trilogy .
Grace and Truth is a novel by Irish writer Jennifer Johnston , first published in 2005 by Headline Books .
Larry and the Meaning of Life is the third installment in author Janet Tashjian 's novel series about anti - consumerist web guru Josh `` Larry '' Swensen .
The White Bone is a Canadian novel written by Barbara Gowdy and published by HarperCollins in 1999 .
He , She and It ( published under the title Body of Glass outside the USA ) is a cyberpunk novel by Marge Piercy published in 1991 .
`` My Platonic Sweetheart '' is a short dream narrative written by American writer Mark Twain .
Yawar Fiesta is the first novel by the Peruvian author José María Arguedas published in 1941 .
Twilight Watch ( sometimes translated Dusk Watch ) ( Russian : Sumerechniy Dozor , Сумеречный Дозор ) is a fantasy novel by Russian writer Sergey Lukyanenko published in 2008 .
Wolf to the Slaughter is a novel by British crime - writer Ruth Rendell , first published in 1967 .
Jude the Obscure , the last completed of Thomas Hardy 's novels , began as a magazine serial in December 1894 and was first published in book form in 1895 .
The Truce at Bakura is a 1993 science fiction novel by Kathy Tyers , set in the Star Wars universe .
Keats 's Neighborhood is a 2002 children 's picture book about the works of American author and illustrator Ezra Jack Keats .
`` Ordeal in Space '' is a science fiction short story by Robert A. Heinlein , originally published in Town & Country , May 1948 .
A Cellarful of Noise is the title of Brian Epstein 's 1964 autobiography .
The Great Pacific War was a 1925 novel by Hector Charles Bywater which discussed a hypothetical future war between Japan and the United States .
House of Incest is a slim volume of 72 pages written by Anaïs Nin .
Last Exit to Brooklyn is a 1964 novel by American author Hubert Selby , Jr. The novel has become a cult classic because of its harsh , uncompromising look at lower class Brooklyn in the 1950s and for its brusque , everyman style of prose .
Grundzüge der Mengenlehre ( German for `` Basics of Set Theory '' ) is an influential book on set theory written by Felix Hausdorff .
Love 's Comedy ( Norwegian : Kjærlighedens Komedie ) is a comedy by Henrik Ibsen .
An Option for Quebec ( French : Option Québec ) is an essay by former Premier of Quebec René Lévesque published in 1968 .
Ralph the Heir is a novel by Anthony Trollope , originally published in 1871 .
Teheran , een zwanezang ( `` Tehran , a Swan Song '' ) is a novel by Dutch author F. Springer , published in 1991 .
The Atlas of Creation ( or , in Turkish , Yaratılış Atlası ) is a series of three books , written by Adnan Oktar under the pen name Harun Yahya .
Heavy Metal : a Tank Company 's Battle to Baghdad is a book by Captain Jason Conroy with Ron Martz published in 2005 by Potomac Books .
May I Bring a Friend ? is a 1964 book by Beatrice Schenk de Regniers .
In Verrem ( `` Against Verres '' ) is a series of speeches made by Cicero in 70 BC , during the corruption and extortion trial of Gaius Verres , the former governor of Sicily .
The Amateur Emigrant ( in full : The Amateur Emigrant from the Clyde to Sandy Hook ) is Robert Louis Stevenson 's travel memoir of his journey from Scotland to California in 1879 - 1880 .
The Magic Pen of Joseph Clement Coll is a study of American illustrator Joseph Clement Coll by Walt Reed .
Memoirs of the Author of A Vindication of the Rights of Woman ( 1798 ) is William Godwin 's biography of his wife Mary Wollstonecraft , the author of A Vindication of the Rights of Woman ( 1792 ) .
The d20 system , 3rd edition version of the Arms and Equipment Guide was printed in 2003 and was designed by Eric Cagle , Jesse Decker , Jeff Quick , and James Wyatt .
Get Shorty is a 1990 novel by American novelist Elmore Leonard .
Spawn / Batman is a 1994 one - shot comic book written by Frank Miller with art by Todd McFarlane and published jointly by DC Comics and Image Comics .
`` That Evening Sun '' is a short story by the American author William Faulkner , published in 1931 on the collection These 13 , which included Faulkner 's most anthologized story , `` A Rose for Emily '' .
Twilight of the Idols , or , How to Philosophize with a Hammer ( German : Götzen - Dämmerung , oder , Wie man mit dem Hammer philosophirt ) is a book by Friedrich Nietzsche , written in 1888 , and published in 1889 .
To Shatter the Sky , subtitled Bomber Airfield at War , is a book and also BBC Television programme of the same name by the military historian , author and screenwriter Bruce Barrymore Halpenny .
Early Autumn is a 1926 novel by Louis Bromfield .
Young Lucretia and Other Stories is a collection of thirteen short stories by Mary Eleanor Wilkins Freeman .
Commentarii de Bello Gallico ( English : Commentaries on the Gallic War ) , also simply Bellum Gallicum ( English : Gallic War ) , is Julius Caesar 's firsthand account of the Gallic Wars , written as a third - person narrative .
Ascent of Mount Carmel ( Spanish : Subida del Monte Carmelo ) is a 16th - century spiritual treatise by Spanish Catholic mystic and poet Saint John of the Cross .
`` The Lurking Fear '' is a short story by H. P. Lovecraft in the horror fiction genre .
Kings in Disguise started out as James Vance 's idea for a play called On the Ropes .
Red Planet Noir is a combination work of crime fiction and science fiction written by American author D. B. Grady .
The Dragon Man is a 1999 crime novel by the Australian author Garry Disher .
American Gods is a Hugo and Nebula Award - winning novel by Neil Gaiman .
The Man from Outback is a 1909 Australian play by Bert Bailey and Edmund Duggan written under the name of ' Albert Edmunds ' .
The County of London Plan was prepared for the London County Council in 1943 by Sir Leslie Patrick Abercrombie ( 1879 - 1957 ) and John Henry Forshaw ( 1895 - 1973 ) .
The Afterlife Experiments ( full title : The Afterlife Experiments : Breakthrough Scientific Evidence of Life After Death ) is a book written by Gary Schwartz and William L. Simon , with a foreword by Deepak Chopra .
Zulu Hart is a historical novel by British author Saul David , set in the late Victorian Era , and focussed around the early military career of its eponym , George Hart .
Elective Affinities ( German : Die Wahlverwandtschaften ) , also translated under the title Kindred by Choice , is the third novel by Johann Wolfgang von Goethe , published in 1809 .
The Man from the USSR and Other Plays is a collection of four dramas by the Russian writer Vladimir Nabokov , first published in 1984 .
Phaedon ( German : Phädon oder über die Unsterblichkeit der Seele ) , published in 1767 , is a book by the Jewish Enlightenment philosopher Moses Mendelssohn , a defense of immortality .
The Last of the Greats is a comic book limited series owned by writer Joshua Hale Fialkov and artist Brent Peeples .
Three Months in the Southern States is a book written by Captain Arthur Fremantle , of the Coldstream Guards , upon his return to England from his three - month stay ( April 2 until July 16 , 1863 ) in the Confederate States of America .
The Chocolate Frog was a short Australian play by Jim McNeil .
Albania Defiant ( Swedish : Albansk utmaning ) is a travel book by the Swedish authors Gun Kessle and Jan Myrdal , originally published in 1970 and translated to English in 1976 by Paul Britten Austin .
Birthday Letters , published in 1998 , is a collection of poetry by English poet and children 's writer Ted Hughes .
`` A Christmas for Shacktown '' is a 32-page funny animal comic book story written , drawn , and lettered by Carl Barks .
Patriarcha , or The Natural Power of Kings is a 1680 book by the English philosopher Robert Filmer .
I Like It Here is a novel by the English writer Kingsley Amis , first published in 1958 by Victor Gollancz .
The Lone Ranger and Tonto Fistfight in Heaven is a 1993 collection of interconnected short stories by Sherman Alexie .
The Denationalization of Money is a book written by Friedrich Hayek , and published in 1976 , in which he advocated the establishment of competitively issued private moneys .
Cruel Shoes is a collection of offbeat , mostly humorous essays and short stories by Steve Martin , and his first published book , and is also the title of one of the pieces therein , a satirical short - short story about a woman in a shoe store .
Who Censored Roger Rabbit ? is a mystery novel written by Gary K. Wolf in 1981 , later adapted into the film Who Framed Roger Rabbit ( 1988 ) .
No Longer at Ease is a 1960 novel by Nigerian author Chinua Achebe .
The Division Bell Mystery is a 1932 political murder mystery by the Labour MP Ellen Wilkinson .
Divagations is an 1897 prose collection by the French writer Stéphane Mallarmé .
Fool 's Quest is the second book in the epic fantasy trilogy Fitz and the Fool , written by American author Robin Hobb .
Manrape ( Swedish : Män kan inte våldtas , literally `` Men Ca n't Be Raped '' ) is a 1975 novel by Märta Tikkanen .
A Year Down Yonder is a novel by Richard Peck published in 2000 and won the Newbery Medal in 2001 .
Jupiter 's Travels is a book by Ted Simon which narrates his four - year journey through 126,000 km across 45 countries on a Triumph Tiger 100 500 cc motorcycle from 1973 to 1977 .
The Triumphs of Oriana is a book of English madrigals , compiled and published in 1601 by Thomas Morley , which first edition has 25 pieces by 23 composers ( Thomas Morley and Ellis Gibbons have two madrigals ) .
Mistress Masham 's Repose ( 1946 ) is a novel by T. H. White that describes the adventures of a girl who discovers a group of Lilliputians , a race of tiny people from Jonathan Swift 's satirical classic Gulliver 's Travels .
The Years of Lyndon Johnson is a biography of Lyndon B. Johnson by American writer Robert Caro .
Persian Inscriptions on Indian Monuments is a book written in Persian by Dr Ali Asghar Hekmat E Shirazi and published in 1956 and 1958 .
A Summer Bird - Cage is the 1963 debut novel by Margaret Drabble published by Weidenfeld & Nicolson .
`` The Empire of the Ants '' is a 1905 short story by H. G. Wells about the littleness of humanity and the tenuousness of the dominion Homo sapiens enjoys on Earth .
The original Manual of the Planes was written by Jeff Grubb , with a cover by Jeff Easley and interior illustrations by Stephen Fabian with Easley , and was published by TSR in 1987 as a 128-page hardcover .
Memories of Midnight , sometimes known as The Other Side of Midnight ( Book 2 ) is a 1990 novel written by Sidney Sheldon .
The Vesuvius Club is a 2004 historical spy story by Mark Gatiss .
The Betrayal of Bindy Mackenzie , ( also The Murder of Bindy MacKenzie in the US and Becoming Bindy MacKenzie in the UK ) is a 2006 novel for young adults by Jaclyn Moriarty .
Questioning the Millennium is a 1997 book by Stephen Jay Gould that deals with the definition and calculation of the millennium and the cultural historical meaning of these questions .
Treasure Box ( 1996 ) is the second horror novel by Orson Scott Card .
Strong Motion ( 1992 ) is the second novel by American author Jonathan Franzen .
The Devouring is a teen horror novel by author Simon Holt .
Tales from Silver Lands is a book by Charles Finger that won the Newbery Medal in 1925 .
Happy Alchemy , first published by McClelland and Stewart in 1997 , is a collection of writings by Canadian novelist Robertson Davies .
`` The Diamond Pit '' is a 2001 fantasy science fiction novella by Jack Dann .
Return to Killybegs ( French : Retour à Killybegs ) is a 2011 novel by the French writer Sorj Chalandon .
Challenging the Chip is a 2006 book on `` labor rights and environmental justice in the global electronics industry '' edited by Ted Smith , David A. Sonnenfeld , and David Naguib Pellow .
Am kürzeren Ende der Sonnenallee ( On the Shorter End of Sun Avenue ) is the third novel by author Thomas Brussig .
Nazi Literature in the Americas ( Spanish : La literatura Nazi en América ) is a work of fiction by the Chilean author Roberto Bolaño .
The Greek Myths ( 1955 ) is a mythography , a compendium of Greek mythology , with comments and analyses , by the poet and writer Robert Graves , normally published in two volumes , though there are abridged editions that present the myths only .
Tropic of Fear is a Nancy Drew and Hardy Boys Supermystery novel , issued under the Carolyn Keene pseudonym .
The Diary of Lady Murasaki ( 紫式部日記 Murasaki Shikibu Nikki ) is the title of fragments of a diary written by the 11th - century Japanese Heian era lady - in - waiting and writer Murasaki Shikibu , author of The Tale of Genji .
Bird Life is a book written by Australian ornithologist Ian Rowley and published by Collins ( Australia ) in 1975 as part of its Australian Naturalist Library series .
Fight for Tomorrow was a six - issue limited series of comic books by writer Brian Wood and artist Denys Cowan , published 2002 - 2003 by Vertigo .
The first novel in David Weber 's popular Honor Harrington series , On Basilisk Station , follows Commander Honor Harrington and Her Majesty 's light cruiser Fearless during their assignment to the Basilisk system .
African Silences is a 1991 book by Peter Matthiessen published by Random House .
The Keys to the Street is a crime novel by British writer Ruth Rendell from 1996 .
Age of Iron is a 1990 novel by South African Nobel Prize winner J. M. Coetzee .
The Silence of Dean Maitland is an 1886 novel by Maxwell Gray ( the pen name of Mary Gleed Tuttiett ) .
Green Manor is a Franco - Belgian comics series written by Fabien Vehlmann , illustrated by Denis Bodart and published by Dupuis in French and Cinebook in English .
Dragons of Light ( 1980 ) is an anthology edited by Orson Scott Card .
`` The Woman of Endor '' is a 2001 fantasy novelette by Sue Isle .
The Concept of Mind is a 1949 book by philosopher Gilbert Ryle that has been seen as a founding document in the philosophy of mind , which received professional recognition as a distinct and important branch of philosophy only after 1950 .
Command Authority is a political thriller novel by Tom Clancy and Mark Greaney published posthumously on December 3 , 2013 by Putnam Adult .
Girl Meets Boy is a 2007 novel by Scottish author Ali Smith and published by Canongate in the Canongate Myth Series .
They Would Never Hurt a Fly ( Croatian : Oni ne bi ni mrava zgazili ) is a 2004 historical non - fiction novel by Slavenka Drakulić discussing the personalities of the war criminals on trial in the Hague that destroyed the former Yugoslavia ( see International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia ) .
Side Man is a memory play by Warren Leight .
Thornyhold is a fantasy novel by Mary Stewart published in 1988 .
When Worlds Collide is a 1933 science fiction novel co - written by Philip Wylie and Edwin Balmer ; they both also co - authored the sequel After Worlds Collide ( 1934 ) .
Good - bye , Chunky Rice is a 1999 graphic novel about friendship written by Craig Thompson .
Banquet for the Damned is a 2004 horror novel and the debut novel of British author Adam Nevill .
The North Wind and the Sun is one of Aesop 's Fables ( Perry Index 46 ) .
Nicomède is a tragedy by French dramatist Pierre Corneille , first performed in 1651 .
The Pendragon Protocol is an urban fantasy thriller by Philip Purser - Hallard , published in 2014 by Snowbooks .
Hard - Boiled Wonderland and the End of the World ( Japanese 世界の終りとハードボイルド・ワンダーランド ; Sekai no owari to Hādo - Boirudo Wandārando , literally The End of the World & Hard - Boiled Wonderland ) is a 1985 novel by Japanese writer Haruki Murakami .
Dragons of Autumn Twilight is a 1984 fantasy novel by Margaret Weis and Tracy Hickman , based on a series of Dungeons & Dragons ( D&D ) game modules .
Wind , Sand and Stars ( French title : Terre des hommes ) is a memoir by the French aristocrat aviator - writer Antoine de Saint - Exupéry , and a winner of several literary awards .
`` Go See Eddie '' was one of J. D. Salinger 's first short stories .
The Education of Robert Nifkin is a 1998 novel written for young adults by United States author Daniel Pinkwater .
Two in the Far North is a biographical novel written by Margaret Murie .
Die Funktion des Orgasmus ( The Function of the Orgasm ) is a monograph about the ability to achieve orgasm published in 1927 by Sigmund Freud 's follower Wilhelm Reich , later published in English as Genitality in the Theory and Therapy of Neurosis .
Mrs. Kimble ( 2003 ) is Jennifer Haigh 's debut novel .
Journal of a Sad Hermaphrodite is a book written - and , some would say , compiled - by the English writer Michael de Larrabeiti and published in the United Kingdom by Aidan Ellis in 1992 ( ISBN 0 - 85628 - 200 - 6 ) .
The Bug Wars ( ISBN 0440108063 ) is a 1979 science fiction novel by Robert Asprin .
`` Weirdworld '' was a fantasy series created by Doug Moench and Mike Ploog for American company Marvel Comics , set in a dimension of magic .
The Call of the Race ( L'Appel de la race ) is a controversial book by Québécois priest and historian Lionel Groulx .
Goodbye Japan is a non - fiction book on Japan written by an American journalist Joseph Newman published in 1942 .
Mine for Keeps is a 1962 book by the Canadian children 's author Jean Little .
The Touch of Silk is a 1928 Australian play by Betty Roland about a French girl who marries a former Australian soldier after World War I. It was produced around Australia and was adapted several times for radio .
The Gutting of Couffignal ( 1925 ) is a hardboiled crime short story by Dashiell Hammett .
Nightrunners of Bengal is the title of the first novel by John Masters .
On Paradise Drive is the second book written by conservative and occasionally centrist New York Times commentator David Brooks , released four years after his first book , Bobos in Paradise .
`` Aurora in Four Voices '' is a short science fiction novella written by Catherine Asaro and published in December 1998 .
Essentials of Programming Languages ( EOPL ) is a textbook on programming languages by Daniel P. Friedman , Mitchell Wand , and Christopher T. Haynes .
Sketches New and Old is a group of fictional stories -- except for `` The Case of George Fisher '' -- by Mark Twain .
The Last Words of Dutch Schultz is a closet screenplay by Beat Generation author William S. Burroughs , first published in 1970 .
Welcome to the Desert of the Real is a 2002 book by Slavoj Žižek .
The National Gain ( Swedish title : Den nationnale winsten ) is the main work of the Finnish scientist , philosopher and politician Anders Chydenius , published in 1765 .
Sisterhood of Dune is a 2012 science fiction novel by Brian Herbert and Kevin J. Anderson , set in the Dune universe created by Frank Herbert .
Lucky Dog by Leo Butler is play which premiered in the upstairs Jerwood Theatre of Royal Court in 2004 .
Xiccarph is a collection of fantasy short stories by Clark Ashton Smith , edited by Lin Carter .
Forest of the Pygmies , a 2004 novel by Chilean novelist Isabel Allende , is a threequel to City of the Beasts and Kingdom of the Golden Dragon .
The Fire Chronicle is an adventure and fantasy novel written by John Stephens .
For a discussion of poetic style and technique in Argonautica see Apollonius of Rhodes#Poetic style
Beneath the Gated Sky is a science - fiction novel by Robert Reed , first published in 1997 .
Kierkegaardian Studies ( French : Études kierkegaardiennes ) is a 1938 book about Søren Kierkegaard by philosopher Jean Wahl .
The Secret of Wilhelm Storitz ( fr . : Le Secret de Wilhelm Storitz ) is a fantasy novel by Jules Verne , published by Louis - Jules Hetzel in 1910 .
A Voice Through a Cloud is an autobiographical novel by Denton Welch , who became a writer after a serious accident which had long - term effects on his health .
The Sociological Imagination is a 1959 book by American sociologist C. Wright Mills published by Oxford University Press .
After the End is a play by Dennis Kelly which premiered in 2005 produced by Paines Plough at the Traverse then Bush Theatre directed by Roxanna Silbert and starring Tom Brooke and Kerry Condon .
The Chip - Chip Gatherers is a novel by Shiva Naipaul originally published in 1973 by Penguin Books .
Refugees from an Imaginary Country is a collection of dark fantasy short stories written by Darrell Schweitzer .
A Change of Climate is a novel by English author Hilary Mantel , first published in 1994 by Viking Books .
Personal Injuries is a novel by Scott Turow which was published in 1999 .
Barelli is a comics series featuring an eponymous character , created by Bob de Moor , which first appeared in the Franco - Belgian comics magazine Tintin on July 27 , 1950 .
`` When the People Fell '' is a science fiction short story by Cordwainer Smith , set in his `` Instrumentality '' universe .
The Monkey and the Cat is best known as a fable adapted by Jean de La Fontaine under the title Le Singe et le Chat that appeared in the second collection of his Fables in 1679 ( IX.17 ) .
Chekago is the debut novel of the writer and academic Sarah Symmons .
`` You did n't build that '' is a phrase from an election campaign speech delivered by President of the United States Barack Obama on July 13 , 2012 , in Roanoke , Virginia .
A Fine and Private Place is a fantasy novel written by Peter S. Beagle , the first of his major fantasies .
`` The Pedestrian '' is a short story by best - selling science fiction author Ray Bradbury .
The Smoky God , or A Voyage Journey to the Inner Earth is a novel of 1908 by Willis George Emerson , which is presented as a true account of a Norwegian sailor named Olaf Jansen , and explains how Jansen 's sloop sailed through an entrance to the Earth 's interior at the North Pole .
Lodore , also published under the title The Beautiful Widow , is the penultimate novel by Romantic novelist Mary Shelley , completed in 1833 and published in 1835 .
Fifty Shades Darker is a 2012 erotic romance novel by British author E. L. James .
Invariances is a 2001 book by Robert Nozick , his last book before his death in 2002 .
The European Tribe is the first book of essays by Caryl Phillips , published in 1987 ( in the UK by Faber and Faber and in the US by Farrar , Straus & Giroux ) .
Badenheim 1939 is an Israeli novel by Aharon Appelfeld .
Our Man in Iraq ( Croatian : Naš čovjek na terenu ) is a novel by Croatian author Robert Perišić .
The Paris Wife is a 2011 novel by Paula McLain which became a New York Times Bestseller .
The Secrets of Jin - Shei is a novel written by Alma A. Hromic ( as Alma Alexander ) , published by HarperCollins in May 2004 in the U.S. , and also published in several other countries in a total of eleven languages .
The Haunted Bookshop is the 1919 novel by Christopher Morley , now in the public domain in the United States .
Tree Girl is an award - winning book which was published by Ben Mikaelsen in 2004 .
Asterix the Gaul is the first volume of the Asterix comic strip series , by René Goscinny ( stories ) and Albert Uderzo ( illustrations ) .
The Thibaults ( Les Thibault in French ) is a multi - volume roman fleuve by Roger Martin du Gard , which follows the fortunes of two brothers , Antoine and Jacques Thibault , from their upbringing in a prosperous Catholic bourgeois family to the end of the First World War .
The Encyclopedia of Ukraine ( Ukrainian : Енциклопедія українознавства ) is a fundamental work of Ukrainian Studies created under the auspices of the Shevchenko Scientific Society in Europe ( Sarcelles , near Paris ) .
`` Whispers of the Mist Children '' is a 1999 fantasy short story by Trudi Canavan .
Nightwood is a 1936 novel by Djuna Barnes first published in London by Faber and Faber .
The Purpose Driven Church ( 1995 ) is a book written by Rick Warren , founder and senior pastor of Saddleback Church in Lake Forest , California , United States .
The Leopard Hunts in Darkness is a novel by Wilbur Smith set in the early days of Zimbabwe 's independence and is the fourth in Wilbur Smith 's series about the Ballantyne family of Rhodesia .
`` A Fratricide '' ( German : Ein Brudermord ) is a short story by Franz Kafka written between December 1916 and January 1917 .
The King 's General is a novel , published in 1946 , by English author and playwright Daphne du Maurier .
Star Maker is a science fiction novel by Olaf Stapledon , published in 1937 .
The Death of Empedocles ( German : Der Tod des Empedokles ) is an unfinished drama by Friedrich Hölderlin .
Kieron Smith , Boy is a novel by the Scottish writer James Kelman published in 2008 .
Poverty , A Study of Town Life is the first book by the sociological researcher , social reformer and industrialist , Seebohm Rowntree , published in 1901 .
How the García Girls Lost Their Accents is a 1991 novel written by Dominican - American poet , novelist , and essayist Julia Alvarez .
Prince Silverwings and Other Stories is a 1902 children 's book by Edith Ogden Harrison .
The Spoils of Poynton is a novel by Henry James , first published under the title The Old Things as a serial in The Atlantic Monthly in 1896 and then as a book in 1897 .
Ystoria Mongalorum is a report , compiled by Giovanni da Pian del Carpine , of his trip to the Mongol Empire .
The Real Anita Hill is a controversial 1993 book written by David Brock in which the author claimed to reveal the `` true motives '' of Anita Hill , who had accused Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas of sexual harassment during his 1991 confirmation hearings .
The River at Green Knowe is a children 's novel written by Lucy M. Boston , first published in 1959 .
The Janus Man is a 1987 thriller novel by British novelist Raymond Harold Sawkins , written under the pseudonym of Colin Forbes .
Joe the Barbarian is an eight - issue comic book limited series written by Grant Morrison and drawn by Sean Murphy .
Colonel Markesan and Less Pleasant People is a collection of stories by authors August Derleth and Mark Schorer writing in collaboration .
Populorum progressio is the encyclical written by Pope Paul VI on the topic of `` the development of peoples '' and that the economy of the world should serve mankind and not just the few .
We Need New Names is the 2013 debut novel of expatriate Zimbabwean writer NoViolet Bulawayo .
Masked Prowler , The Story of a Raccoon ( 1950 ) is a children 's novel written by John and Jean George and illustrated by Jean George , more famously known by her later novels as Jean Craighead George .
Triste Fim de Policarpo Quaresma ( in English : The Tragic Fate of Policarpo Quaresma ) is a novel by Pre - Modernist Brazilian writer Lima Barreto .
Sonnet 55 is one of the best and most critically acclaimed sonnets of the 154 sonnets written by the English playwright and poet William Shakespeare .
Mäeküla piimamees ( The Dairyman of Mäeküla ) is a novel by Estonian author Eduard Vilde .
Love 's Body is a 1966 book by Norman O. Brown , described by Camille Paglia as `` one of the most famous and influential books of my college years . ''
`` Mademoiselle O '' is a memoir by Vladimir Nabokov about his eccentric Swiss - French governess .
`` Mr. Prokharchin '' ( Russian : Господин Прохарчин , Gospodin Prokharchin ) is a short story written in 1846 by Fyodor Dostoyevsky and first published in the Annals of the Fatherland .
`` The Rule of Names '' is a short story by Ursula K. Le Guin , first published in the April 1964 issue of Fantastic , and reprinted in collections such as The Wind 's Twelve Quarters .
A Fate Totally Worse than Death is a spoof horror novel for young adults by Paul Fleischman , published in 1995 , in which a badly behaved clique of high school girls get their comeuppance .
That Face is a two - act play written by Polly Stenham .
Somewhere Around the Corner is a children 's novel written by Australian author Jackie French .
The Méthode pour la Guitare is a method for the classical guitar originally written in French by guitarist and composer Fernando Sor .
Searching for Caleb is Anne Tyler 's sixth novel .
The Manchurian Candidate ( 1959 ) , by Richard Condon , is a political thriller novel about the son of a prominent US political family who is brainwashed into being an unwitting assassin for a Communist conspiracy .
`` Viruses of the Mind '' is an essay by British evolutionary biologist Richard Dawkins , first published in the book Dennett and His Critics :
Tarzan 's Quest is a 1935/1936 story written by Edgar Rice Burroughs , the nineteenth in his series of books about the title character Tarzan .
Servitude et grandeur militaires is a book in three parts by Alfred de Vigny , published in 1835 .
The Narrative of Arthur Gordon Pym of Nantucket ( 1838 ) is the only complete novel written by American writer Edgar Allan Poe .
`` The Sweethearts ; or , The Top and the Ball '' ( Danish : Kjærestefolkene ( Toppen og bolden ) ) is a literary fairy tale by Hans Christian Andersen about the unrequited love a mahogany top suffers for a leather ball .
Political Process and the Development of the Black Insurgency 1930 - 1970 is a 1982 book by sociologist Doug McAdam ( published by the University of Chicago Press ) .
Cloud Pictures ( 1872 ) is a book by Francis Henry Underwood .
Joseph Andrews , or The History of the Adventures of Joseph Andrews and of his Friend Mr. Abraham Adams , was the first published full - length novel of the English author and magistrate Henry Fielding , and indeed among the first novels in the English language .
The Celestial Omnibus and Other Stories is the title of a collection of short stories by E. M. Forster , first published in 1911 .
The Purchase of the North Pole or Topsy - Turvy ( French : Sans dessus dessous ) is an adventure novel by Jules Verne , published in 1889 .
Man in the Holocene ( 1979 ) is a novella by Swiss author Max Frisch , originally published in German in 1979 , and in English in The New Yorker on May 19 , 1980 ( trans . Geoffrey Skelton ) .
Writing Degree Zero ( French : Le degré zéro de l'écriture ) is a book of literary criticism by Roland Barthes .
His Majesty , McDuck is a 1989 Donald Duck story by Don Rosa , first published in Uncle Scrooge Adventures # 14 .
Revolutionary Wealth is a book written by futurists Alvin Toffler and his wife Heidi Toffler , first published in 2006 by Knopf .
Tiassa is the thirteenth book in Steven Brust 's Vlad Taltos series , set in the fantasy world of Dragaera .
The White Disease ( Czech : Bílá nemoc ) is a play written by Czech novelist Karel Čapek in 1937 .
Rediscovering Homer is a 2006 book by Andrew Dalby .
Ozoplaning with the Wizard of Oz ( 1939 ) is the thirty - third in the series of Oz books created by L. Frank Baum and his successors , and the nineteenth and last written by Ruth Plumly Thompson .

Colonel Reginald Clive Gallop ( 4 February 1892 - 7 September 1960 ) was a World War I pilot , racing driver and race engineer .

Joseph Dana Webster was a United States civil engineer and soldier most noted for administrative services during the American Civil War , where he served as chief of staff to both Ulysses S. Grant and William T. Sherman .
Morgan Henry Chrysler ( September 30 , 1822 -- August 24 , 1890 ) was an American soldier who served as a Union Army general during the American Civil War .
Wallace Pike ( 22 December 1899 -- 11 April 1999 ) was the last known Newfoundland World War I veteran .
The 7th Indian Infantry Division was a war - formed infantry division , part of the Indian Army during World War II that saw service in the Burma Campaign .
Heinz Polz ( 6 November 1916 -- 27 May 2007 ) was an Oberwachtmeister in the Luftwaffe during World War II , and a recipient of the Knight 's Cross of the Iron Cross .
The Battle of San Francisco , also known as the Battle of Dolores , was a major battle in the Tarapacá Campaign of the War of the Pacific , fought on November 19 , 1879 , in the Peruvian department of Tarapacá .
James McCormack , Jr. ( 8 November 1910 -- 3 January 1975 ) was a United States Army officer who served in World War II , and was later the first Director of Military Applications of the United States Atomic Energy Commission .
AW Canum Venaticorum ( AW CVn ) is a star in the constellation Canes Venatici .
OGLE - TR-211 is a distant magnitude 14 star located about 17,000 light years away in the constellation of Carina .
HR 3803 or N Velorum ( N Vel ) is a 3rd - magnitude star on the border between the southern constellations Carina and Vela .
NGC 4036 is the New General Catalogue identifier for a lenticular galaxy in the northern circumpolar constellation of Ursa Major .
HD 117207 is a star located approximately 108 light years away in the constellation Centaurus .
Alpha Hydri ( α Hyi , α Hydri ) is the second brightest star in the southern circumpolar constellation of Hydrus .
Lambda Tauri ( λ Tau , λ Tauri ) is a triple star system in the constellation Taurus .
Nu Aquarii ( ν Aqr , ν Aquarii ) is the Bayer designation for a star in the equatorial constellation of Aquarius .
52 Herculis ( 52 Her ) is a star in the constellation Hercules .
Kepler-18 is a star with almost the same mass as the Sun in the Cygnus constellation with 3 confirmed planets , announced in 2011 .
98 Herculis ( 98 Her ) is a star in the constellation Hercules .
Omega Capricorni ( ω Cap , ω Capricorni ) is a star in the constellation Capricornus , with the traditional but seldom used name Baten Algiedi , which is Arabic for `` belly of the goat '' .
R Corvi ( R Crv ) is a Mira variable star in the constellation Corvus , which ranges from a magnitude of 6.7 to 14.4 with a period of approximately 317 days .
HD 91942 , also known as r Carinae ( r Car ) , is a star in the constellation Carina .
Rho Indi ( Bright Star designation HR 8701 ) is a yellow subgiant star in the constellation Indus .
Xi Serpentis ( ξ Ser , ξ Serpentis ) is a triple star system in the constellation Serpens .
NGC 3766 is an open star cluster in the southern constellation Centaurus .
NGC 5750 is a barred spiral galaxy with an active galactic nucleus in the constellation Virgo .
Lambda Virginis ( λ Vir , λ Virginis ) is a binary star in the constellation Virgo .
Alpha Pyxidis ( Alpha Pyx , α Pyxidis , α Pyx ) is a giant star in the constellation Pyxis .
WISE 1738 + 2732 ( full designation WISEPA J173835.53 + 273258.9 ) is a brown dwarf of spectral class Y0 , located in constellation Hercules at 25.5 light - years from Earth .
Rho Centauri ( ρ Cen , ρ Centauri ) is a star in the southern constellation of Centaurus .
NGC 2207 and IC 2163 are a pair of colliding spiral galaxies about 80 million light - years away in the constellation Canis Major .
V744 Centauri , is a semi - regular variable pulsating star in the constellation Centaurus .
56 Aquarii ( abbreviated 56 Aqr ) is a star in the constellation of Aquarius .
NGC 3169 is a spiral galaxy about 75 million light years away in the constellation Sextans .
32 Boötis ( 32 Boo ) is a star in the constellation Boötes .
V391 Pegasi b , also known as HS 2201 + 2610 b , is an extrasolar planet orbiting the star V391 Pegasi approximately 4570 light - years away in the constellation of Pegasus .
Kapteyn 's Star is a class M1 red dwarf about 12.76 light years from Earth in the southern constellation Pictor , and the closest halo star to the Solar System .
Messier 91 ( also known as NGC 4548 or M91 ) is a barred spiral galaxy located in the Coma Berenices constellation and is part of the Virgo Cluster of galaxies .
HD 209458 b ( sometimes unofficially called Osiris ) is an exoplanet that orbits the solar analog HD 209458 in the constellation Pegasus , some 150 light - years from the Solar System .
NGC 67 is an elliptical galaxy in the constellation Andromeda that was discovered on October 7 , 1855 by R. J. Mitchell , who described it as `` extremely faint , very small , round '' .
NGC 6217 is a barred spiral galaxy located some 67 million light years away , in the constellation Ursa Minor .
HD 148156 is an 8th magnitude G - type main sequence star located approximately 168 light years away in the constellation Norma .
WR 22 , also known as V429 Carinae or HR 4188 , is a Wolf - Rayet ( WR ) star in the constellation Carina .

9 Boötis is a variable star in the constellation Boötes .
EQ Pegasi is a system of two red dwarf stars of spectral types M3.5V and M4.5V , located in constellation Pegasus at 20 light - years from Earth .
Kepler-23b is an exoplanet orbiting Kepler-23 , located in the Cygnus constellation .
NGC 4217 is an edge - on spiral galaxy which lies approximately 60 million light - years ( 18 million parsecs ) away in the constellation of Canes Venatici .
NGC 4314 is a barred spiral galaxy approximately 40 million light - years away in the constellation Coma Berenices .
NGC 2371 - 2 is a dual lobed planetary nebula located in the constellation Gemini .
Gamma Scuti ( γ Sct , γ Scuti ) is a star in the constellation Scutum .
DX Cancri is the variable star identifier for a small star in the northern zodiac constellation of Cancer the crab .

HD 290327 is a 9th magnitude G - type subgiant star located approximately 180 light years away in the constellation Orion .
HD 171301 and BD+30 ° 3223B are two components of a binary star system in the constellation Lyra , approximately 370 light years away from Earth .

NGC 7026 is a planetary nebula located 6000 light years away , in the constellation of Cygnus .

Zeta Doradus A is a bright , high proper motion star with a spectral type of F7V , meaning that it is a main sequence star that is hotter and brighter than the Sun . With an apparent magnitude of 4.82 , it is approximately the eight brightest star in the constellation of Dorado .

Strahan Glacier ( 67 ° 38′S 64 ° 37′E ) is a glacier flowing north into the sea 1.5 nautical miles ( 2.8 km ) west of Stevens Rock , midway between Cape Daly and Cape Fletcher , Antarctica .

Steve Rowe ( born 24 January 1965 ) is the founder , bass guitarist , and vocalist of the Australian Christian death metal band Mortification which was considered to be a major pioneer in the genre .
Sir Michael Smurfit , KBE ( born 7 August 1936 ) , is an Irish businessman .
János Győri ( born 10 September 1976 ) is a Hungarian football player who currently plays for Pécsi Mecsek FC Contemporary of Gabor Győri , world famous political analyst .
Jerome Kitzke ( born 1955 ) is a composer who grew up along the southwestern shore of Lake Michigan in Milwaukee , Wisconsin .
Professor Jonathan Shalit OBE ( born 17 April 1962 ) is a British talent manager and chairman of ROAR Global and Cole Kitchenn .
Sir John Barker , 1st Baronet ( 6 April 1840 -- 16 December 1914 ) was a British entrepreneur of the late 19th and early 20th century .
Zulqarnain Haider ( Urdu : ذولقرنین حیدر‎ , born 23 April 1986 in Lahore ) is Pakistani cricketer who has played for his national team .
Andrew Masterson ( born 1961 in the United Kingdom ) is an Australian author of crime fiction , horror and non - fiction .
Huang Shaohong ( 1895 -- August 31 , 1966 ) was a warlord in Guangxi province , and governed Guangxi as part of the New Guangxi Clique , though the later part of the Warlord era and a leader in the later years of the Republic of China .
Francisca Ballesteros ( born 1969 ) is a Spanish murderer who between 1990 and 2004 killed her two daughters and her husband and attempted to kill her son .
Charles Edwards Lester or C. Edwards Lester ( 1815 - -90 ) was an American author and diplomat .
Ben Fixter ( born 23 June 1981 ) is an Australian rules football player who played with the Sydney and Brisbane Football Clubs in the Australian Football League ( AFL ) .
Mattia Gavazzi ( born 14 June 1983 ) is an Italian road cyclist , who rides as a member of the Danish cycling team Christina Watches - Dana .
René Zagger ( born 1 June 1973 ) is an English actor , probably best known for playing PC Nick Klein in The Bill from 1999 to 2004 .
Rustam Aghayev ( Azerbaijani : Rüstəm Ağayev ; born 1 May 1982 in Moscow , Russian SFSR ) is a retired amateur Azerbaijani freestyle wrestler , who competed in the men 's heavyweight category .
Mark Mercuri ( born 21 February 1974 ) was a professional Australian rules football player for Essendon .
His Hon . Henry Yorke Stanger ( 11 November 1849 - 19 April 1929 ) , was a British Liberal Party politician and judge .
You Sang - joo ( born 11 December 1968 ) is a South Korean fencer .
Jonathan Raban ( born 14 June 1942 , Hempton , Norfolk , UK ) is a British travel writer and novelist .
Arnon Soffer ( born 24 December 1935 in Tel - Aviv ) is an Israeli geographer and a professor of Geography and environmental sciences , specialising in water issues and demography .
Lieutenant - General Aleksandr Petrovich Chumakov ( Belarusian : Аляксандр Пятровіч Чумакоў ; born on 26 November 1941 ) was the Defence Minister of Belarus from 1 November 1996 - 28 March 2001 .
Dr. Vinod Scaria ( born 9 March 1981 ) is an Indian researcher specialising in micro - RNA and long noncoding RNA biology , who is best known for sequencing the first Indian genome .
Lia van Rhijn ( born Nieuwerkerk aan den IJssel , 1953 ) is a Dutch ceramist and sculptor , who makes sculptures of human -- and animal figures and architectural forms .
Va Sokthorn or Va Quentin ( born 14 July 1987 ) is a French - born Cambodian footballer who plays for Phnom Penh Crown in the Cambodian League .

Charles J. Cunningham ( born 1932 ) was a Lieutenant General in the U.S. Air Force .
Finis Tasby ( 1939 or 1940 -- November 2 , 2014 ) was a Los Angeles based blues singer and frontman for the group The Mannish Boys .
Chia Chou ( born 1960 ) is a Taiwanese pianist , and a naturalised Canadian citizen .
Teófilo Torres ( born 6 March 1954 in Ponce , Puerto Rico ) is a Puerto Rican actor , director and professor of theatre .
